        "rich_text_PJHfJt": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>A solitaire ring is known for its simplicity. It highlights a single diamond with minimal distractions.</p><p>Adding a halo changes the overall personality of the ring.</p><p>With a classic halo, the ring becomes more dramatic and eye-catching. The additional diamonds create a strong sparkle effect.</p><p>With a hidden halo, the ring keeps its solitaire appearance but gains extra brilliance when viewed from different angles.</p><p>Some people prefer the timeless look of a solitaire, while others enjoy the added detail that a halo brings.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_mEE3FU": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Should You Upgrade Your Solitaire Ring to a Halo?",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Should You Upgrade Your Solitaire Ring to a Halo?</h2><p>Upgrading to a halo setting is a common choice, especially for engagement rings or anniversary upgrades.</p><p>However, it depends on what you want from the ring.</p><p>You might consider upgrading if you:</p><p>1.] Want your diamond to appear larger<br/>2.] Prefer more sparkle<br/>3.]Enjoy detailed designs<br/><br/>But if you love the clean, minimal look of a solitaire ring, a halo might not be necessary.</p><p>Some people also choose hidden halos as a middle ground -  they get extra sparkle without changing the overall look too much.<br/><br/></p>",
            "custom_id": "should-you",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_qYycBL": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Which Diamond Shapes Work Best With Halo Settings",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Which Diamond Shapes Work Best With Halo Settings</h2><p>Halo settings work well with many diamond shapes, but some shapes benefit more than others.</p><p>Round diamonds are the most common choice because they maximize sparkle.</p><p>Oval and cushion shapes also look beautiful with halos because the surrounding diamonds enhance their shape.</p><p>Emerald and radiant cuts can also be paired with halos, especially when the goal is to add more brilliance around the stone.</p>",
            "custom_id": "which-diamond",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_VTxqqr": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Why Many Modern Jewelry Buyers Prefer Hidden Halos",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Why Many Modern Jewelry Buyers Prefer Hidden Halos</h2><p>In recent years, many people have shifted toward hidden halo designs.</p><p>The reason is simple -  they feel more subtle and contemporary. Instead of immediately seeing a ring full of diamonds, you notice the center stone first.</p><p>Then, when the ring moves or catches light from the side, the hidden halo appears.</p><p>This small detail gives the ring a unique character without making it feel overly decorative.</p>",
            "custom_id": "why-many",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
